@startmindmap
title GitHub Copilot Customization

* GitHub Copilot\nCustomization

** Instruction Levels
*** Org Instructions\n[GitHub.com only | no IDE effect]
**** Use: coding standards, security tone, OWASP, naming conventions
**** Enable in VS Code: organizationInstructions.enabled=true
*** Personal Instructions\n[GitHub.com only | you only]
**** Use: personal tone, language preference, quick team testing
*** Repo-Wide\n.github/copilot-instructions.md\n[always-on | all IDEs + GitHub.com]
**** Use: tech stack, naming, arch patterns, security, error handling, docs
**** NOT for: one-off tasks, user input/variables, conditional rules, multi-step workflows
**** Also: AGENTS.md (open standard), CLAUDE.md (Claude Code compat)
*** Path-Specific\n.github/instructions/NAME.instructions.md\n[glob pattern via applyTo]
**** Frontmatter: name (opt), description (opt), applyTo glob (opt)
**** Use: language-specific rules, framework patterns, dir-specific standards
**** NOT supported in: JetBrains, Xcode, GitHub.com chat, mobile

** Reusable Task Files
*** Prompt Files\n.github/prompts/*.prompt.md\n[on-demand | explicit invoke only]
**** Frontmatter: mode (ask/edit/agent), description, tools[]
**** Dynamic vars: ${input:varName:placeholder}
**** Invoke: /filename in chat, Attach context menu, /instructions menu
**** Use: one-off tasks, user input needed, code gen, refactor, analysis
**** NOT for: persistent behavior, auto-run tasks, complex autonomous workflows
**** Supported: VS Code, Visual Studio, JetBrains ONLY
**** AI generate: /create-prompt in chat
*** Agent Skills\nskills/<name>/SKILL.md\n[auto-invoked by intent | open standard]
**** Frontmatter: name* (req), description* (req), license, compatibility, metadata, allowed-tools
**** NOT supported: mode, tools, model, dynamic vars
**** Progressive loading: name+desc at startup (~100 tokens), body on activation
**** Use: reusable shareable expertise, cross-session availability, team workflows
**** NOT for: one-off tasks, user input needed, mode/tool/model control
**** Supported: Claude Code, VS Code, JetBrains + compatible agents

** Agents
*** Custom Agents\n.github/agents/*.agent.md\n[full autonomous workflow]
**** Frontmatter: name, description, tools[], model[] (priority order), handoffs[]
**** handoffs: label, agent, prompt, send true/false
**** Repo agents: commit to default branch → github.com/copilot/agents
**** VS Code agents: chat.agentFilesLocations setting
**** Use: multi-step tasks, sustained context, code review, multi-file refactor
**** NOT for: one-off tasks, broad behavioral guidance
**** AI generate: /create-agent in chat
**** Old name: .chatmode.md (rename to .agent.md)
*** AGENTS.md\n[plain markdown | no schema | open standard]
**** Linux Foundation standard | 20+ tools support
**** Purpose: README for agents — build, test, conventions
*** Agent Plugins\n[preview | VS Code marketplace]
**** Bundles: slash commands, skills, agents, hooks, MCP servers
**** Structure: plugin.json, skills/, agents/, hooks/, scripts/, .mcp.json
**** Install: @agentPlugins in Extensions or Chat: Install Plugin From Source
**** Cross-tool: works in VS Code, Copilot CLI, Claude Code
**** Caution: can run code on machine — review before install

** MCP Servers\n.vscode/mcp.json\n[workspace-scoped]
*** Config fields: type (stdio/http/sse), command, args, env
*** Reference in agent tools: servername/* or servername/toolname
*** Secrets: use ${input:varName} or VS Code secret storage — never hardcode
*** Example use: daily-tasks prompt via GitHub MCP → Tasks.md file

** Hard Limits
*** 4,000 chars max per instruction file for PR code review (silently ignored beyond)
*** ~1,000 lines soft limit before quality degrades
*** No external URL fetching in instructions — copy content directly
*** Inline autocomplete NOT affected by instructions (chat only)
*** PR review uses BASE branch instructions only
*** Both repo-wide + path-specific applied when both match same file

** Best Practices
*** Start with 10–20 instructions, iterate one at a time
*** Keep tools[] minimal in agents
*** Separate planning agents from implementation agents
*** Define explicit scope limits + escalation behavior in agents
*** Avoid conflicting instructions across files (behavior is non-deterministic)
*** Split repo-wide (cross-cutting) vs path-specific (language/dir) concerns
*** Fix non-working instructions: make specific+imperative, shorten file, resolve conflicts
*** Anti-patterns: applyTo:'**' for lang rules, stale library refs, 2000-line files, conflicting files

@endmindmap